WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.800 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:05.530 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.530 --> 00:00:10.240 align:middle line:84%
>> "Thinking Allowed,"
conversations on the leading

00:00:10.240 --> 00:00:14.200 align:middle line:84%
edge of knowledge and discovery,
with psychologist Jeffrey

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:15.000 align:middle line:90%
Mishlove.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:31.533 align:middle line:90%


00:00:31.533 --> 00:00:32.450 align:middle line:90%
>> Hello, and welcome.

00:00:32.450 --> 00:00:33.910 align:middle line:90%
I'm Jeffrey Mishlove.

00:00:33.910 --> 00:00:36.250 align:middle line:84%
This is part 2 of
our two-part program

00:00:36.250 --> 00:00:41.290 align:middle line:84%
on cross-cultural spirituality
with Joan Halifax, Roshi

00:00:41.290 --> 00:00:46.240 align:middle line:84%
of the Upaya Zen Center in Santa
Fe, New Mexico, anthropologist,

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:50.740 align:middle line:84%
and author of a number of books,
including "Shamanic Voices,"

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:53.650 align:middle line:84%
"The Fruitful Darkness,"
"The Human Encounter

00:00:53.650 --> 00:00:59.140 align:middle line:84%
with Death," "Being with
Dying," and "A Buddhist

00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:01.180 align:middle line:90%
Life in America."

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:02.110 align:middle line:90%
Welcome, Joan.

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:03.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you, Jeffrey.

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:06.340 align:middle line:84%
>> In part 1, of our
two-part program,

00:01:06.340 --> 00:01:08.350 align:middle line:90%
you told a fascinating story.

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:09.850 align:middle line:84%
We didn't quite
finish it, and I'd

00:01:09.850 --> 00:01:13.600 align:middle line:84%
like to share it again with
our viewers, of the encounter

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:16.900 align:middle line:84%
between RD Laing, the great
psychiatrist, and founder

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:20.620 align:middle line:84%
of what some people call
the antipsychiatry movement,

00:01:20.620 --> 00:01:23.620 align:middle line:90%
and your Zen teacher.

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.410 align:middle line:90%
>> The story was--

00:01:26.410 --> 00:01:30.800 align:middle line:84%
I remember the story because
you asked me about teachers.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:32.005 align:middle line:90%
Who were my teachers?

00:01:32.005 --> 00:01:34.570 align:middle line:90%


00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:36.020 align:middle line:90%
Or what were my teachers?

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:38.790 align:middle line:84%
And so the story
was that Seungsahn,

00:01:38.790 --> 00:01:40.210 align:middle line:90%
who is a Zen teacher--

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:41.360 align:middle line:90%
>> A Korean Zen teacher.

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:42.160 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:45.340 align:middle line:84%
And he was my first teacher,
my first Buddhist teacher.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:47.490 align:middle line:84%
And he was at the
Ojai Foundation,

00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:49.630 align:middle line:90%
and he was giving a lecture.

00:01:49.630 --> 00:01:52.360 align:middle line:84%
And in the audience,
sitting beside me,

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:57.970 align:middle line:84%
was psychiatrist RD Laing,
and Ronnie was just snarling,

00:01:57.970 --> 00:01:59.830 align:middle line:90%
as he was wont to do.

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:02.920 align:middle line:84%
And, at a certain
point, in the midst of--

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:06.260 align:middle line:84%
middle of Seungsahn's
lecture, he said, excuse me.

00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:11.050 align:middle line:84%
And Seungsahn stopped and looked
at him, and Ronnie snarled,

00:02:11.050 --> 00:02:13.360 align:middle line:90%
you're no teacher.

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:17.320 align:middle line:84%
And Seungsahn picked up
his stick, and he said,

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:19.390 align:middle line:90%
does the Sun teach you?

00:02:19.390 --> 00:02:21.490 align:middle line:90%
And Liang said, yes.

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:22.520 align:middle line:90%
Do the stars teach you?

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:23.320 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:24.580 align:middle line:90%
Does the Moon teach you?

00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:25.380 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:26.500 align:middle line:90%
Does the grass teach you?

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:27.300 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:28.540 align:middle line:90%
Do the trees teach you?

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.370 align:middle line:90%
Yes, said Liang.

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:33.276 align:middle line:84%
He said, well, if they
teach you, then I teach you.

00:02:33.276 --> 00:02:36.132 align:middle line:90%
[JEFFREY LAUGHS]

00:02:36.132 --> 00:02:40.480 align:middle line:84%
>> And the point being that
you yourself have learned from

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:42.840 align:middle line:84%
the forests, and from the
deserts, and the mountains.

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:44.380 align:middle line:90%
>> Everything.

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:49.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, one of the most
important qualities

00:02:49.450 --> 00:02:54.235 align:middle line:84%
that arises in meditation
is a mind of inquiry.

00:02:54.235 --> 00:02:58.720 align:middle line:90%


00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:01.620 align:middle line:84%
In the Zen Peacemaker
Order, Tetsugen Roshi,

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:04.260 align:middle line:84%
Glassman Roshi calls
it not knowing.

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:06.680 align:middle line:84%
Suzuki Roshi called
it beginner's mind.

00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:10.960 align:middle line:84%
It's that mind which is
open and interested in--

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:12.860 align:middle line:90%
awake to the world.

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:18.250 align:middle line:84%
And so, from that point of
view, everything is teaching us.

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:19.810 align:middle line:84%
But from another
point of view, there

00:03:19.810 --> 00:03:22.270 align:middle line:84%
have been particular
individuals who

00:03:22.270 --> 00:03:26.170 align:middle line:84%
have been very important
in my life as teachers.

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:31.062 align:middle line:84%
And, of course,
Glassman Roshi has--

00:03:31.062 --> 00:03:34.390 align:middle line:84%
I have a very profound
relationship with,

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:37.810 align:middle line:84%
and grateful for
his faith in me.

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:40.060 align:middle line:84%
And Thich Nhat Hahn, who
is my second Buddhist

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:42.910 align:middle line:84%
teacher, and Seungsahn,
my first Buddhist teacher.

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:46.840 align:middle line:84%
Many other teachers, and
friends, and scholars.

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:51.850 align:middle line:84%
And even my ex-husband, Stan
Grof, I learned so much from.

00:03:51.850 --> 00:03:53.020 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:54.460 align:middle line:90%
>> But it is true that--

00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:58.320 align:middle line:90%


00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:03.300 align:middle line:84%
I think that the natural world,
so to speak, the wilderness,

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:10.620 align:middle line:84%
continues to be my greatest
friend and the teacher

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:12.090 align:middle line:90%
I feel closest to.

00:04:12.090 --> 00:04:14.850 align:middle line:84%
>> There is a sense in
the spiritual traditions

00:04:14.850 --> 00:04:18.839 align:middle line:84%
of the world that people
sometimes need to push

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:21.269 align:middle line:84%
themselves outside
of their own skin,

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:23.850 align:middle line:84%
outside of the limitations
they think they have,

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:26.580 align:middle line:84%
and certainly outside
of the conditionings

00:04:26.580 --> 00:04:28.050 align:middle line:90%
of their particular culture.

00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:31.170 align:middle line:84%
And this is done through
initiation rituals,

00:04:31.170 --> 00:04:34.710 align:middle line:84%
through fasting, and
solitude, and many things.

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:38.370 align:middle line:84%
My sense of your path is that
you've gone around the world

00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:40.740 align:middle line:84%
in every direction,
pushing yourself

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:44.880 align:middle line:84%
beyond what certainly an outside
observer might have thought

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:46.770 align:middle line:90%
were your limits.

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:50.340 align:middle line:84%
>> There's a line from the
"Tao Te Ching" that goes,

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:55.520 align:middle line:84%
going on means going far,
going far means returning.

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:57.360 align:middle line:90%
And I think it is true that--

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:01.590 align:middle line:90%


00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:08.320 align:middle line:84%
I was a war baby, and
in my 20s in the '60s.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:14.850 align:middle line:84%
And it brought about a
certain quality of mind which

00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:16.950 align:middle line:90%
was fundamentally initiatic.

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:20.280 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to go down and in.

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:22.410 align:middle line:84%
My emphasis in my
whole life, really,

00:05:22.410 --> 00:05:25.410 align:middle line:84%
has been about exploring
suffering, partly

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:28.200 align:middle line:84%
because I've experienced
a lot of suffering,

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.260 align:middle line:84%
and partly because
my heart breaks

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:33.280 align:middle line:90%
in the presence of suffering.

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:35.520 align:middle line:84%
So working with dying
people, or working

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:38.670 align:middle line:84%
in the penitentiary system,
on death row and maximum

00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:42.150 align:middle line:84%
security, which I currently
do, is a way for me

00:05:42.150 --> 00:05:52.720 align:middle line:84%
to continue to deepen, deepen
my experience of compassion.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:57.106 align:middle line:90%
And I think, without that--

00:05:57.106 --> 00:05:59.100 align:middle line:84%
you were saying I
live on the edge.

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:02.250 align:middle line:84%
And I said, when you're on
the edge, you don't know it.

00:06:02.250 --> 00:06:07.290 align:middle line:84%
But without that impulse to
go down and in, whether it's

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:12.150 align:middle line:84%
into the really dark places of
our society, of our culture,

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:15.270 align:middle line:84%
or of a human life,
or of my own life,

00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:19.050 align:middle line:84%
or into a place of
suffering like Tibet,

00:06:19.050 --> 00:06:22.800 align:middle line:90%
I think that I would just--

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.540 align:middle line:84%
I would have no
reason, really, to--

00:06:24.540 --> 00:06:29.430 align:middle line:84%
I mean, just the idea of a
house, and a car, and a bank

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:34.140 align:middle line:84%
account, and a good job, and
the country club, it just--

00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:36.480 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's just--

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:40.170 align:middle line:90%
it's not-- it's trivial.

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:43.440 align:middle line:84%
>> You've gone way beyond
that a long time ago.

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:49.230 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, but it's interesting,
because my parents valued that.

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:51.210 align:middle line:84%
And, really, without
them valuing that,

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:53.190 align:middle line:84%
I couldn't have
gone beyond that.

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:57.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was their
incredible hard work

00:06:57.450 --> 00:06:59.520 align:middle line:84%
which made it possible
for me to, in a way,

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:03.330 align:middle line:84%
to jettison everything
that was important to them.

00:07:03.330 --> 00:07:09.330 align:middle line:84%
But, in a way, to not
abandon my culture at all.

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:20.410 align:middle line:84%
I feel that-- part of the
work that spiritual people

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:24.730 align:middle line:84%
in this country, part of the
work that is opening up to us

00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:27.750 align:middle line:84%
is what's called
engaged spirituality.

00:07:27.750 --> 00:07:30.640 align:middle line:84%
It's not just a
cross-cultural exoticism,

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:32.830 align:middle line:84%
but it's how can we
put our good hearts

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:35.270 align:middle line:90%
into service for the world?

00:07:35.270 --> 00:07:39.220 align:middle line:84%
How can we help with
education, for example?

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:42.820 align:middle line:84%
How can we help in terms
of medical services?

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:45.790 align:middle line:84%
What can we do to create
a justice system that's

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:47.950 align:middle line:90%
compassionate, not punitive?

00:07:47.950 --> 00:07:53.950 align:middle line:84%
How can we create
practices of caregiving

00:07:53.950 --> 00:07:57.340 align:middle line:84%
that leave caregivers
intact, and honor

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:59.560 align:middle line:90%
the experience of dying?

00:07:59.560 --> 00:08:02.620 align:middle line:84%
I think that we have an
extraordinary opportunity

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:08.410 align:middle line:84%
with the current abundance in
our country to really refine

00:08:08.410 --> 00:08:12.250 align:middle line:84%
a gift to society that
has to do with moving

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:15.370 align:middle line:84%
into a sort of post-industrial
vision of compassion

00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:18.160 align:middle line:84%
in the world, of
act of compassion.

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:20.590 align:middle line:84%
And my life hasn't
really, Jeffrey,

00:08:20.590 --> 00:08:23.830 align:middle line:84%
been so much about an
exploration of the exotic,

00:08:23.830 --> 00:08:27.520 align:middle line:84%
but I've used, if you will, the
strange, the alien wilderness

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:33.020 align:middle line:84%
or culture as a way to kind
of expose my psyche to myself,

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:35.770 align:middle line:84%
which I couldn't do with
conventional psychological

00:08:35.770 --> 00:08:38.440 align:middle line:90%
strategies in an adequate way.

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:43.900 align:middle line:84%
And, in the process of this,
really seeing this life

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:46.870 align:middle line:84%
is really about
helping other beings.

00:08:46.870 --> 00:08:49.510 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, you're
wearing Buddhist robes.

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:52.750 align:middle line:84%
And although you've traveled
to many parts of the world

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:56.470 align:middle line:84%
and been in many cultures,
the Buddhist spiritual path

00:08:56.470 --> 00:08:59.560 align:middle line:84%
seems to be the
one that fits you.

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:01.880 align:middle line:90%
>> It's so practical, Jeffrey.

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:03.340 align:middle line:90%
I mean, this is--

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:06.520 align:middle line:84%
when I read DT Suzuki and
Alan Watts in the '60s,

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:10.690 align:middle line:84%
it was a thing that just
completely made it real for me,

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:14.380 align:middle line:84%
that there was an
absence of obfuscation,

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:17.830 align:middle line:84%
that it was practical, that
it met in a certain way

00:09:17.830 --> 00:09:19.420 align:middle line:90%
my needs as a woman.

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:22.930 align:middle line:84%
That it wasn't involved so
much in the experience of faith

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:25.660 align:middle line:84%
that I, who had been
brought up as a Christian,

00:09:25.660 --> 00:09:30.280 align:middle line:84%
had been pressed into, and I
even went to church school.

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:32.830 align:middle line:90%


00:09:32.830 --> 00:09:38.560 align:middle line:84%
And Zen practice, I've studied
with some really extraordinary

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:40.300 align:middle line:90%
Tibetan teachers.

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:42.340 align:middle line:84%
And I did this
after Zen practice,

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:44.140 align:middle line:84%
doing a lot of Zen
practice, because I

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:49.150 align:middle line:84%
wanted to have more
concrete teachings.

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:53.110 align:middle line:84%
And then I began to read the
sutra, the direct teachings

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:55.600 align:middle line:84%
of the Buddha, after studying
with Tibetan teachers,

00:09:55.600 --> 00:09:58.960 align:middle line:84%
because I realized that the
core teachings of the Buddha

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:01.100 align:middle line:84%
made such extraordinary
sense to me.

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:03.130 align:middle line:90%
They weren't exotic at all.

00:10:03.130 --> 00:10:05.410 align:middle line:84%
They just work
cross-culturally, which I think

00:10:05.410 --> 00:10:08.230 align:middle line:84%
is why Buddhism has moved into
so many different cultures

00:10:08.230 --> 00:10:10.780 align:middle line:90%
successfully.

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:14.230 align:middle line:84%
And what's happening with
Buddhism in America today is

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:17.770 align:middle line:84%
fascinating, because it's
being, in a very positive way,

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:19.660 align:middle line:84%
secularized through,
for example,

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:21.760 align:middle line:84%
work like Jon
Kabat-Zinn is doing,

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:23.817 align:middle line:84%
or I'm doing in the
penitentiary system, or--

00:10:23.817 --> 00:10:25.150 align:middle line:90%
>> What is Jon Kabat-Zinn doing?

00:10:25.150 --> 00:10:29.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Jon Kabat-Zinn
works, in a huge way,

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:34.330 align:middle line:84%
with stress reduction using
Buddhist meditative strategies

00:10:34.330 --> 00:10:39.220 align:middle line:84%
as a way to help individuals
work with the mind-body

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:40.870 align:middle line:90%
conflict.

00:10:40.870 --> 00:10:43.570 align:middle line:84%
And working in the
penitentiary, which

00:10:43.570 --> 00:10:51.620 align:middle line:84%
has been a very inspiring and
challenging experience for me.

00:10:51.620 --> 00:10:54.220 align:middle line:84%
Which-- in a way,
our penitentiaries

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:58.720 align:middle line:90%
are like downbeat monasteries.

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:05.350 align:middle line:84%
And I work in maximum security,
in a men's maximum security

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:08.770 align:middle line:84%
facility in New Mexico,
and on death row, where men

00:11:08.770 --> 00:11:11.300 align:middle line:90%
are locked down 23 hours a day.

00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:14.470 align:middle line:84%
So this is a very
interesting opportunity

00:11:14.470 --> 00:11:18.970 align:middle line:84%
to work with individuals who
are in fundamental isolation.

00:11:18.970 --> 00:11:20.700 align:middle line:84%
>> Joan, we'll
come back to that--

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:20.980 align:middle line:90%
>> OK

00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:21.813 align:middle line:90%
>> --after a minute.

00:11:21.813 --> 00:11:23.570 align:middle line:90%
We're going to take a break.

00:11:23.570 --> 00:11:25.222 align:middle line:90%
We'll be back.

