00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:35.340 align:middle line:90%
I'm your host, Jeffrey Mishlove.

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:39.840 align:middle line:84%
My guest is Joan Halifax,
Roshi of the Upaya Zen

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:42.120 align:middle line:90%
Center in Santa Fe, New Mexico.

00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:43.615 align:middle line:90%
Actually, Abiquiu, I think.

00:11:43.615 --> 00:11:44.490 align:middle line:90%
>> No, it's Santa Fe.

00:11:44.490 --> 00:11:45.870 align:middle line:90%
>> Santa Fe?

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:50.480 align:middle line:84%
And she is author of
"Being with Dying,"

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.380 align:middle line:84%
"The Fruitful Darkness,"
and other books.

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:55.110 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about
cross-cultural approaches

00:11:55.110 --> 00:11:56.650 align:middle line:90%
to spirituality.

00:11:56.650 --> 00:12:00.120 align:middle line:84%
And we were talking about your
work in the penitentiaries,

00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:01.830 align:middle line:84%
and much of your
work, a great deal,

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:03.720 align:middle line:90%
has been with dying people.

00:12:03.720 --> 00:12:06.300 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right, Jeffrey.

00:12:06.300 --> 00:12:09.960 align:middle line:84%
I started this--
this sort of began

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:12.660 align:middle line:84%
to open for me when
my grandmother died,

00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:15.060 align:middle line:90%
who was an extraordinary woman.

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:19.770 align:middle line:84%
And she herself had been
involved with dying people.

00:12:19.770 --> 00:12:20.910 align:middle line:90%
It's a long story.

00:12:20.910 --> 00:12:22.620 align:middle line:90%
I won't go into the whole thing.

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:25.740 align:middle line:84%
>> You talked about how
she made the sculptures

00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:26.600 align:middle line:90%
for the cemetery--

00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:27.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:12:27.810 --> 00:12:28.930 align:middle line:90%
>> --in Augusta, Georgia.

00:12:28.930 --> 00:12:29.790 align:middle line:90%
>> In Savannah.

00:12:29.790 --> 00:12:30.630 align:middle line:90%
>> Savannah.

00:12:30.630 --> 00:12:34.380 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, Bonaventure Cemetery.

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:36.960 align:middle line:84%
And then working
in a medical school

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:38.910 align:middle line:84%
at the University of
Miami School of Medicine.

00:12:38.910 --> 00:12:40.950 align:middle line:90%
And then with Stan in the--

00:12:40.950 --> 00:12:43.540 align:middle line:84%
>> Stan Grof, the psychiatrist,
your former husband.

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:44.340 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:12:44.340 --> 00:12:47.360 align:middle line:84%
In the project using LSD as
an adjunct to psychotherapy.

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:48.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Legally.

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:49.200 align:middle line:90%
>> Legally, right.

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:51.810 align:middle line:90%


00:12:51.810 --> 00:12:59.160 align:middle line:84%
And I was young when I
was doing this, and it--

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:01.680 align:middle line:84%
nothing in my culture
prepared me, really,

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:04.590 align:middle line:90%
for being with dying.

00:13:04.590 --> 00:13:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And what has evolved for me,
Jeffrey, through the years,

00:13:08.160 --> 00:13:13.850 align:middle line:84%
is very deep contemplative
work using Buddhist meditation,

00:13:13.850 --> 00:13:16.120 align:middle line:84%
various strategies
from Buddhism,

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:20.130 align:middle line:84%
which has a profound emphasis
on the encounter with death.

00:13:20.130 --> 00:13:23.100 align:middle line:84%
>> It seems to me that, more
than any other spiritual

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:25.890 align:middle line:84%
tradition, the Buddhists
have explored the nature

00:13:25.890 --> 00:13:29.760 align:middle line:84%
of the dying process,
and the moment of death,

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:30.780 align:middle line:90%
and the afterlife--

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:31.580 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:34.320 align:middle line:84%
>> --in greater detail,
particularly the Tibetan

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:35.250 align:middle line:90%
Buddhists.

00:13:35.250 --> 00:13:37.140 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, yes, Indeed.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:40.980 align:middle line:84%
And I think that the
Tibetan Buddhist traditions

00:13:40.980 --> 00:13:43.740 align:middle line:84%
around death were
deeply influenced

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:49.060 align:middle line:84%
by the Bon tradition, the
shamanic traditions of Tibet.

00:13:49.060 --> 00:13:50.460 align:middle line:90%
Indeed.

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:52.320 align:middle line:84%
But there are many
strategies, even

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:55.590 align:middle line:84%
in the early sutras of
the Buddha, which I think

00:13:55.590 --> 00:13:59.610 align:middle line:84%
are extraordinarily helpful for
caregivers and dying people.

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:03.750 align:middle line:84%
So my work, since I practiced
Zen Buddhism, Tibetan,

00:14:03.750 --> 00:14:05.610 align:middle line:84%
and also studied
Theravadan Buddhism,

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:07.710 align:middle line:84%
and was familiar
with the sutras,

00:14:07.710 --> 00:14:12.510 align:middle line:84%
has been to follow those threads
in the different Buddhist

00:14:12.510 --> 00:14:17.100 align:middle line:84%
schools related to
being with dying,

00:14:17.100 --> 00:14:20.820 align:middle line:84%
and to develop meditational
strategies, a number

00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:22.350 align:middle line:84%
of meditational
strategies that are

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:25.380 align:middle line:84%
effective for caregivers
and dying people.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:28.523 align:middle line:84%
And we have an extraordinary
training program

00:14:28.523 --> 00:14:29.940 align:middle line:84%
for health care
professionals that

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:33.990 align:middle line:84%
has been going on for years
that's extremely intensive.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:35.430 align:middle line:90%
I'm teaching these strategies.

00:14:35.430 --> 00:14:39.510 align:middle line:84%
And, also, we have programs
for dying people as well.

00:14:39.510 --> 00:14:42.300 align:middle line:90%


00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:45.360 align:middle line:84%
It's just very
interesting, because it's

00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:47.970 align:middle line:84%
one thing when you're
working with someone

00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:50.250 align:middle line:84%
who is a so-called
stranger, and you're

00:14:50.250 --> 00:14:52.320 align:middle line:84%
a compassionate
stranger being present

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:55.350 align:middle line:84%
for this person and
his or her family.

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:58.540 align:middle line:84%
But it's another thing
when it's your own family.

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:05.370 align:middle line:84%
And it's been a very interesting
experience for me personally

00:15:05.370 --> 00:15:14.040 align:middle line:84%
to reconcile the struggle around
my own father's dying and death

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:16.630 align:middle line:90%
and my Buddhist practice.

00:15:16.630 --> 00:15:19.290 align:middle line:84%
And was also true with
my mother's death.

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:21.960 align:middle line:84%
What I've realized
is that grieving

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:26.520 align:middle line:84%
is a very important
phase or experience

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:28.440 align:middle line:90%
for us to go through.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:34.830 align:middle line:84%
Again, it unlocks a kind
of depth inside of one

00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:37.350 align:middle line:84%
which can't be
tapped until you have

00:15:37.350 --> 00:15:39.960 align:middle line:90%
experienced a profound loss.

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:48.510 align:middle line:84%
And it makes you
potentially freer.

00:15:48.510 --> 00:15:50.190 align:middle line:84%
The value of grief,
I think, is not

00:15:50.190 --> 00:15:52.410 align:middle line:90%
well understood in our culture.

00:15:52.410 --> 00:15:56.160 align:middle line:84%
>> I recently interviewed
Rachel Naomi Remen,

00:15:56.160 --> 00:15:59.330 align:middle line:84%
a doctor who also
works with dying.

00:15:59.330 --> 00:16:01.140 align:middle line:84%
And she made a
statement that she

00:16:01.140 --> 00:16:05.190 align:middle line:84%
felt nothing will transform
Western culture more than if we

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:10.530 align:middle line:84%
learn how to listen to people
who are going through the dying

00:16:10.530 --> 00:16:11.870 align:middle line:90%
process.

00:16:11.870 --> 00:16:17.460 align:middle line:84%
>> Jeffrey, I think
that is so, so accurate.

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:20.580 align:middle line:84%
Listening or bearing
witness, being

00:16:20.580 --> 00:16:24.810 align:middle line:84%
present for a
person who is dying,

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:27.700 align:middle line:90%
and not trying to fix it.

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:31.160 align:middle line:84%
Simply being present for
the truth of impermanence

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:34.970 align:middle line:84%
requires an extraordinary
amount of strength.

00:16:34.970 --> 00:16:40.100 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes we have it,
and sometimes we don't.

00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:44.677 align:middle line:84%
And it's-- as someone else
is dying, we're also dying.

00:16:44.677 --> 00:16:45.960 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:48.200 align:middle line:84%
I'm under the impression,
from your work,

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:51.650 align:middle line:84%
that there have been times
when you have sat through--

00:16:51.650 --> 00:16:54.740 align:middle line:84%
with people dying, and
it was a horrible death,

00:16:54.740 --> 00:17:00.350 align:middle line:84%
and you felt like the learning
of that was a very great one.

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:03.005 align:middle line:84%
>> And there's also,
Jeffrey, a very--

00:17:03.005 --> 00:17:05.690 align:middle line:90%


00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:06.980 align:middle line:90%
on one level--

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:08.839 align:middle line:90%
I call it radical optimism.

00:17:08.839 --> 00:17:13.040 align:middle line:84%
There are many situations
that we can do nothing with.

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:15.710 align:middle line:90%
We can't make them better.

00:17:15.710 --> 00:17:17.614 align:middle line:84%
When I'm sitting in
the penitentiary,

00:17:17.614 --> 00:17:20.030 align:middle line:84%
I have to have that
sensibility within me,

00:17:20.030 --> 00:17:22.640 align:middle line:84%
or I couldn't go
back again and again.

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:25.940 align:middle line:84%
But on the other side of
it is that, when a person

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:27.740 align:middle line:90%
is suffering, and even though--

00:17:27.740 --> 00:17:32.000 align:middle line:84%
maybe their suffering can't be
alleviated, the least I can do

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.030 align:middle line:84%
is pray that they will
benefit in some way

00:17:35.030 --> 00:17:37.280 align:middle line:90%
from what they're going through.

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:40.250 align:middle line:84%
And maybe it doesn't
make any difference

00:17:40.250 --> 00:17:42.680 align:middle line:84%
on the sort of
functional level to them,

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:45.230 align:middle line:90%
but there is something about--

00:17:45.230 --> 00:17:47.870 align:middle line:84%
well, one great
Buddhist teacher said,

00:17:47.870 --> 00:17:52.040 align:middle line:84%
there are-- the two really
great practices of meditation

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:55.520 align:middle line:84%
are meta, which is
loving kindness,

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:59.120 align:middle line:84%
and maranasati, which
is being with dying.

00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:02.090 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
being with dying

00:18:02.090 --> 00:18:06.980 align:middle line:84%
is an experience where, if
loving kindness isn't present,

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:09.410 align:middle line:90%
then desperation arises.

00:18:09.410 --> 00:18:12.860 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the existential
philosophers imply that

00:18:12.860 --> 00:18:17.840 align:middle line:84%
the human condition itself is
predicated upon the fact that

00:18:17.840 --> 00:18:19.820 align:middle line:84%
we are all mortal,
we will all die.

00:18:19.820 --> 00:18:26.180 align:middle line:84%
And we have, deep in our hearts,
fear, and misgiving, and denial

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:27.910 align:middle line:90%
around that.

00:18:27.910 --> 00:18:30.800 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, there's another
vision too, and that is,

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:33.920 align:middle line:84%
from the Buddhist point of view,
death is the supreme moment

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:35.690 align:middle line:90%
for enlightenment.

00:18:35.690 --> 00:18:40.340 align:middle line:84%
And great practitioners
live their whole life

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:43.280 align:middle line:84%
for the moment of death,
when the body drops off

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:46.490 align:middle line:84%
and the mind ground
is ultimately free.

00:18:46.490 --> 00:18:50.150 align:middle line:90%
And I feel that this is--

00:18:50.150 --> 00:18:51.920 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is a
vision that I have

00:18:51.920 --> 00:18:56.720 align:middle line:84%
seen realized by
westerners, not just stories

00:18:56.720 --> 00:18:59.150 align:middle line:90%
of Zen masters and yogis.

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:01.580 align:middle line:84%
But I have seen some
extraordinary deaths

00:19:01.580 --> 00:19:07.430 align:middle line:84%
in the now 30 years of bearing
witness with dying people.

00:19:07.430 --> 00:19:11.300 align:middle line:84%
I think that we have
underestimated profoundly

00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:13.490 align:middle line:90%
the human spirit.

00:19:13.490 --> 00:19:18.740 align:middle line:84%
And I feel that a peaceful
and present individual

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:21.530 align:middle line:84%
can, in the midst
of great suffering,

00:19:21.530 --> 00:19:25.940 align:middle line:84%
bring about a quality
of wisdom which is

00:19:25.940 --> 00:19:30.320 align:middle line:90%
inherent to every individual.

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:34.130 align:middle line:84%
And there have
been moments I feel

00:19:34.130 --> 00:19:36.690 align:middle line:84%
that's happened in my
interactions with people,

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:41.090 align:middle line:84%
and there are moments when
it's definitely not happened.

00:19:41.090 --> 00:19:43.280 align:middle line:90%
One just does the best one can.

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:47.330 align:middle line:84%
>> You practice a form of
meditation which is, in effect,

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:49.790 align:middle line:90%
a preparation for dying.

00:19:49.790 --> 00:19:54.320 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the meditation
is dying, in fact.

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:57.500 align:middle line:84%
It's dying to the past, and
It's dying to the future.

00:19:57.500 --> 00:19:59.450 align:middle line:84%
It's coming into the
present, and letting

00:19:59.450 --> 00:20:05.070 align:middle line:84%
the continuum of phenomena just
play on the ground of the mind.

00:20:05.070 --> 00:20:07.970 align:middle line:84%
But one of the
qualities that I feel

00:20:07.970 --> 00:20:12.950 align:middle line:84%
is so important to develop
in Zen meditation practice

00:20:12.950 --> 00:20:16.800 align:middle line:90%
is radiant compassion.

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:19.610 align:middle line:84%
And this is one of the
gifts that I received

00:20:19.610 --> 00:20:25.190 align:middle line:84%
from Tibetan culture, and also
from some of the Indigenous

00:20:25.190 --> 00:20:28.190 align:middle line:84%
teachers that have
touched my life.

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:32.150 align:middle line:84%
To bring into this quality
of bare attention, which

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:36.980 align:middle line:84%
is the ground of Zen
practice, the experience

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:40.330 align:middle line:84%
of radiant compassion, and to
marry the two, if you will.

00:20:40.330 --> 00:20:42.090 align:middle line:90%
>> Radiant compassion.

00:20:42.090 --> 00:20:44.120 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:20:44.120 --> 00:20:46.940 align:middle line:84%
>> How-- can you elaborate
on that a little more?

00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:49.892 align:middle line:90%
It sounds as if there is a--

00:20:49.892 --> 00:20:52.220 align:middle line:84%
something specific, say,
with regard to the radiant.

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:57.730 align:middle line:90%


00:20:57.730 --> 00:21:00.190 align:middle line:90%
>> When I say radiant--

00:21:00.190 --> 00:21:03.040 align:middle line:90%
compassion is non-duality.

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:06.550 align:middle line:84%
As one great teacher
said, it's a meltdown,

00:21:06.550 --> 00:21:13.690 align:middle line:84%
a complete meltdown, where
love and sadness unite.

00:21:13.690 --> 00:21:15.790 align:middle line:90%
And that's what I feel.

00:21:15.790 --> 00:21:20.740 align:middle line:84%
It's the radiance of love, but
it's also the incredible sorrow

00:21:20.740 --> 00:21:26.260 align:middle line:84%
that we feel that so
many of all beings,

00:21:26.260 --> 00:21:28.420 align:middle line:84%
really, in one way or
another, are suffering.

00:21:28.420 --> 00:21:31.960 align:middle line:84%
Even His Holiness,
the Dalai Lama.

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:34.270 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure his heart is broken
about all the suffering

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:39.898 align:middle line:84%
in his country, even though
he has immense equanimity.

00:21:39.898 --> 00:21:44.590 align:middle line:84%
>> But, Joan Halifax, my sense
from being with you is that

00:21:44.590 --> 00:21:48.910 align:middle line:84%
part of your radiant
compassion here is being open,

00:21:48.910 --> 00:21:51.070 align:middle line:84%
vulnerable to your
own suffering,

00:21:51.070 --> 00:21:57.310 align:middle line:84%
and being willing to be right
on the surface with it makes you

00:21:57.310 --> 00:22:02.170 align:middle line:84%
compassionate to the suffering
of others around you.

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:07.420 align:middle line:84%
>> The challenge, Jeffrey,
is not to be taken away

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:09.310 align:middle line:90%
by the world.

00:22:09.310 --> 00:22:16.130 align:middle line:84%
And I don't always meet the
challenge, I really don't.

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:19.750 align:middle line:84%
And that is why
I practice daily.

00:22:19.750 --> 00:22:21.490 align:middle line:84%
And it is why I
go on pilgrimage,

00:22:21.490 --> 00:22:24.640 align:middle line:84%
and it's why I go to my
little hermit's cabin,

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:26.890 align:middle line:84%
and why I turn to
the sutras, and why

00:22:26.890 --> 00:22:30.190 align:middle line:84%
I sit with dying people,
and why I go to prison.

00:22:30.190 --> 00:22:33.110 align:middle line:90%
Because I'm not free.

00:22:33.110 --> 00:22:37.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, it's an honest
statement, and one, I think,

00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:40.720 align:middle line:84%
honestly, Joan, that makes
you, in my estimation,

00:22:40.720 --> 00:22:43.940 align:middle line:84%
one of the great American
teachers of spiritual

00:22:43.940 --> 00:22:44.740 align:middle line:90%
traditions.

00:22:44.740 --> 00:22:45.540 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you.

00:22:45.540 --> 00:22:47.950 align:middle line:84%
>> Thank you so much
for being with me.

00:22:47.950 --> 00:22:51.400 align:middle line:84%
It's really been a
heartfelt experience.

00:22:51.400 --> 00:22:53.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you, Jeffrey.

00:22:53.530 --> 00:22:56.480 align:middle line:84%
>> And thank you
for being with us.

00:22:56.480 --> 00:23:00.430 align:middle line:90%
